section.para:
			The scorer takes the text and the spans to leave out. With a dictionary, a
			token one known confusion repair away from a word is reported as misspelled,
			the shape optical recognition damage takes; adjacent findings merge into one
			span:

Set<String> words = Set.of("modern", "times");
NoiseScorer scorer = new StructuralNoiseScorer(words::contains);

String text = "rnodern tirnes and zxkcvbnmsdfg";
for (NoiseSpan noise : scorer.score(text, List.of())) {
    System.out.println(noise.severity() + " " + noise.span());
}

			This prints one line per finding; rnodern tirnes repairs to the
			two dictionary words through the rn to m confusion
			and merges into one span, and the mash carries two agreeing structural
			signals:

misspelled [0..14)
gibberish [19..31)

			Without a dictionary the same call reports only the gibberish: the misspelled
			tier demands evidence, not guesses.
			NoiseManualExampleTest asserts the behavior shown here.

NoiseAnnotator provides opennlp:noise. In its default mode it requires opennlp:assets and excludes those spans from scoring, so an embedded binary is explained once, by the asset layer, and never again as noise. The standalone mode scores the whole text and requires nothing:
Document document = new AssetAnnotator().annotate(Document.of(text)); document = new NoiseAnnotator().annotate(document);
List<Annotation<NoiseSpan>> noise = document.get(NoiseAnnotator.NOISE);
Because findings are spans on a layer, masking composes directly: replacing the covered characters of every noise annotation with a fixed character renders an unreadable stretch as, for example, a run of stars, with every offset unchanged.
